fields.description:
As app developers for Confluence Cloud apps we would like to have a UI on a general page that only has the global sidebar but not the Confluence sidebar
 # Define the general page in the app descriptor:
{code:java}
{
    ...
    "modules": {
        "generalPages": [
            {
                "key": "my-general-page",
                "url": "/index.html",
                "name": {
                    "value": "My General Page"
                }
            }
        ]
    }
}
{code}

 # Go to the general page: /plugins/servlet/ac/<app-key>/my-general-page

The page has both the slim, blue global sidebar and the wide, blue Confluence sidebar.

We would like to configure the general page so that it only has the slim, global sidebar, because we would like to draw our own sidebar for our UI (inside the iframe, gray, similar to the space sidebar you get when looking at a page).

h3. Summary

When using the endpoint {{/rest/api/content}} to create a lot of pages at the same time. This is easily replicable by doing a simple for loop:

{code}
const httpClient = addon.httpClient(req).asUser("admin");
let n = 100;
for(let i =0 ; i<n; i++) {
    httpClient.post({
        headers: {
            "X-Atlassian-Token": "nocheck",
        },
        json:
            {
                body:
                    {
                        storage:
                            {
                                representation: "storage",
                                value:
                                    "<p>Something</p>"
                            }
                    },
                space: { key: "SPACE_KEY" },
                title: `Page ${i} of ${n}`,
                type: "page"
            },
        url: "/rest/api/content",
    }, function (error, response, body) {
        console.log('==========================================================');
        console.log(`Error: ${JSON.stringify(error, null, 2)}`);
        console.log(`Response: ${JSON.stringify(response, null, 2)}`);
        console.log(`Body: ${JSON.stringify(body, null, 2)}`);
        console.log('==========================================================');
    });
}
{code}

